<br>
How are we to understand Neo's apparent powers outside of the Matrix, where he is supposedly free and thus, merely human. It is true that a possible explanation is that the reality of Zion and Neo's world outside the Matrix might also be a Matrix in a way, a set of defined rules and laws, which govern the physical laws of the dimension. While I think that this twist would make for an interesting conclusion to the trilogy, I have to wonder about something else. <br>
<br>
The Architect seems to intimate that Neo's powers and abilities inside the Matrix are somehow pre-ordained. The Architect also implies that Neo’s ability to influence the code of the Matrix is some sort of latent gift, one that no mathematical formula could accurately predict or quantify. From where exactly then does this ability derive? It cannot be somehow imprinted onto an individual by the Matrix itself, as, if such were the case, the potential for such abilities would be systematically bred out of the gene pool. It can merely be contained, by limiting the number of choices available to the One. If that is true, then Neo’s powers in the Matrix must be somehow genetically inborn. To a certain degree, this fact is implied by some of the script in the first Matrix, with references to Anderson always feeling like he has been looking for something and even some of the psychically gifted children in the Oracle’s apartment.<br>
<br>
The acceptance of this fact would lead one to understand Neo as a superhero figure, born with a unique ability to influence reality in the Matrix and perform godlike tasks. <br>
<br>
If it is possible then for a human to possess the innate ability to telepathically modify a reality governed by the set of laws defined as the Matrix, why then is it not possible for a human to possess the innate ability to telepathically modify a reality governed by the set of laws defined as Reality? Why does it have to be another Matrix for Neo to be able to use his powers? Perhaps his powers also extend to the outside world as well. Perhaps he is not merely superhuman in the Matrix, but he is superhuman in every sense of the word.<br>
<br>
The Architect’s soliloquy in the Monitor Room points to the fact that while the Matrix cannot adequately quantify the impact of chaos, it can set up a system of control over the expected consequences (forcing the One into a dire choice of genocide or servitude). The anomaly, or rather the chaos effect, for which the Architect seems to have designed his trap to prevent, can thus be understood as evolution. Neo’s superhuman ability is an evolutionary reaction to the potential extinction of his species. <br>
<br>
 Leaving the important question regarding his destruction of the Sentinels aside for a moment, and focusing on Neo’s ability, the path that the film’s narrative has set for us begs to ask the question, why? Why was Neo born with these powers? Whether or not, or however he chooses to use them is a moot point in a sense. He has no choice.<br>
<br>
The answer to why Neo chooses to do what he chooses to do is, quite simply put, Love. While I am will not go into the specifics of that thesis now, I think that the Matrix, at its heart is a love story. Neo’s moment of self-realization, and thus, the continuation of his path to enlightenment, is when he chooses to save Trinity rather than save the human race.<br>
